</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3756501103E7311FCBAFE27DDC0ACDC" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD0368A103E7311FCBAFE27DDC0ACDC" blockId="14.[835,1474,477,821]" lastBlockId="15.[113,753,190,471]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103E7310FCBAFE27DCD2ACFF" bold="true" box="[835,967,477,501]" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103E7310FCBAFE27DCAAACFF" bold="true" box="[835,959,477,501]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">Discussion</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
— Members of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F4D09103E7310FAFBFE24DA83ACFF" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1865" box="[1282,1430,478,501]" class="Insecta" family="Nepidae" genus="Laccotrephes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103E7310FAFBFE24DA83ACFF" box="[1282,1430,478,501]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">Laccotrephes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are broad-bodied, dorso-ventrally flattened water scorpions, generally brown or grey in colouration, which resemble dead leaves (
<figureCitation id="13542A0F103E7310FC6DFDC7DCF6AF5F" box="[916,995,573,597]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[836,871,2060,2082]" captionTargetBox="[835,1473,862,2037]" captionTargetId="figure-215@14.[835,1476,859,2040]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 30. Laccotrephes simulatus Montandon, male, specimen from Malaysia, Johor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5351534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5351534/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). The genus contains 66 currently recognised species (exclusive of subspecies) occurring throughout the Paleotropical and southern Palearctic regions, with the vast majority of species endemic to Africa (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFE4B7B103E7310FACFFD67DCE5AFDF" author="Polhemus, J" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" pagination="379 - 391" refId="ref20634" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; D. A. Polhemus, 2008. Global diversity of true bugs (Heteroptera: Insecta) in freshwater. Hydrobiologia, 595: 379 - 391." type="journal article" year="2008">Polhemus &amp; Polhemus, 2008</bibRefCitation>
). The four species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F4D09103E7310FB32FD44DA4DAFDF" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1865" box="[1227,1368,702,725]" class="Insecta" family="Nepidae" genus="Laccotrephes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103E7310FB32FD44DA4DAFDF" box="[1227,1368,702,725]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">Laccotrephes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurring in 
<collectingCountry id="F378761A103E7310FC98FD27DCD8AFFF" box="[865,973,733,757]" name="Singapore" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">Singapore</collectingCountry>
and Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="F378761A103E7310FB86FD27DBF4AFFF" box="[1151,1249,733,757]" name="Malaysia" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
vary widely in size, from the large 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F4D09103E7310FC1AFD04DB73AE1F" baseAuthorityName="Ferrari" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[995,1126,766,789]" class="Insecta" family="Nepidae" genus="Laccotrephes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pfeiferiae">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103E7310FC1AFD04DB73AE1F" box="[995,1126,766,789]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">L. pfeiferiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(over 
<quantity id="4C979B6F103E7310FB57FD07DBECAE1F" box="[1198,1273,765,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="35.0">35 mm</quantity>
in body length) to the small 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F4D09103E7310FC53FCE4DB3EAE3F" authorityName="Montandon" authorityYear="1913" box="[938,1067,798,821]" class="Insecta" family="Nepidae" genus="Laccotrephes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simulatus">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103E7310FC53FCE4DCACAE3F" box="[938,953,798,821]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103E7310FC3CFCE4DB3EAE3F" box="[965,1067,798,821]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">simulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(less than 
<quantity id="4C979B6F103E7310FB64FCE7DBF3AE3F" box="[1181,1254,797,821]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
in body length), and generally inhabit standing pools amid submerged leaf litter. In certain cases multiple species may occur together in the same pool, such as at Mawai in 
<collectingRegion id="49ABF868103F7311FE30FF04DD11AC1C" box="[457,516,254,278]" country="Malaysia" name="Johor" pageId="15" pageNumber="40">Johor</collectingRegion>
where 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F4D09103F7311FDAAFEFADDFCAC1D" baseAuthorityName="Ferrari" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[595,745,255,279]" class="Insecta" family="Nepidae" genus="Laccotrephes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="archipelagi">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103F7311FDAAFEFADD77AC1D" box="[595,610,256,279]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="40">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103F7311FD96FEFADDFCAC1D" box="[623,745,256,279]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="40">archipelagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F4D09103F7311FF88FEDADFE1AC3D" authorityName="Montandon" authorityYear="1913" box="[113,244,287,311]" class="Insecta" family="Nepidae" genus="Laccotrephes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simulatus">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103F7311FF88FEDADF95AC3D" box="[113,128,288,311]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="40">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103F7311FF77FEDADFE1AC3D" box="[142,244,288,311]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="40">simulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F4D09103F7311FED1FEDADECEAC3D" authorityName="Nieser, Zettel &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2009" box="[296,475,287,311]" class="Insecta" family="Nepidae" genus="Laccotrephes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicaudatus">
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103F7311FED1FEDADE22AC3D" box="[296,311,288,311]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="40">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B91BEA98103F7311FEBDFEDADECEAC3D" box="[324,475,288,311]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="40">longicaudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were found intermixed in the same sample. The most recent works on this group are those of Polhemus &amp; Keffer (1999), 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFE4B7B103F7311FDF2FEA4DDB1AC7C" author="Keffer, S" box="[523,676,350,374]" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" pagination="142 - 172" refId="ref19359" refString="Keffer, S. L., 2004. Morphology and evolution of waterscorpion male genitalia (Heteroptera: Nepidae). Systematic Entomology, 29: 142 - 172." type="journal article" year="2004">Keffer (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFE4B7B103F7311FD4BFEA4DFAEAC9C" author="Zettel, H" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" pagination="127 - 132" refId="ref21383" refString="Zettel, H., 2008. Laccotrephes robustior sp. n. (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Nepidae), a new large water scorpion from India. Zeitschrift der Arbeitsgemeinschaft Osterreichischer Entomologen, 60: 127 - 132." type="journal article" year="2008">Zettel (2008)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFE4B7B103F7311FF0EFE84DED8AC9C" author="Nieser, N" box="[247,461,382,406]" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" pagination="11 - 20" refId="ref20284" refString="Nieser, N., H. Zettel &amp; P. - p. Chen, 2009. Notes on Laccotrephes Stal, 1866 with the description of a new species of the L. griseus group (Insecta: Heteroptera: Nepidae). Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, 110 B: 11 - 20." type="journal article" year="2009">Nieser et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, but no current revision of this genus is available for Southeast Asia, making species determinations problematic within the genus as a whole.
</paragraph>
